**Qui-Gon Jinn** is a [fictional character](/wiki/Fictional_character
"Fictional character") in the [_Star Wars_ franchise](/wiki/Star_Wars "Star
Wars"), portrayed by [Liam Neeson](/wiki/Liam_Neeson "Liam Neeson") as one of
the main protagonists of the 1999 film _[Star Wars: Episode I – The Phantom
Menace](/wiki/Star_Wars:_Episode_I_%E2%80%93_The_Phantom_Menace "Star Wars:
Episode I – The Phantom Menace")_.[1]

## Depiction[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: Depiction")]

### Films[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=2 "Edit
section: Films")]

#### _The Phantom Menace_ (1999)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-
Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=3 "Edit section: The Phantom Menace \(1999\)")]

Qui-Gon is one of the main [characters](/wiki/Protagonist "Protagonist") in
the first episode of the [prequel trilogy](/wiki/Prequel_trilogy "Prequel
trilogy"), _[Star Wars: Episode I – The Phantom
Menace](/wiki/Star_Wars:_Episode_I_%E2%80%93_The_Phantom_Menace "Star Wars:
Episode I – The Phantom Menace")_. He is a Jedi Master and mentor of [Obi-Wan
Kenobi](/wiki/Obi-Wan_Kenobi "Obi-Wan Kenobi"). Unlike other, more
conservative Jedi, he values living in the moment as the best way to embrace
[the Force](/wiki/The_Force "The Force"). Jinn is not a member of the [Jedi
Council](/wiki/Jedi_Council "Jedi Council"), despite being among the wisest
and most powerful of the Jedi.

_The Phantom Menace_ opens with Qui-Gon and his apprentice, called a padawan,
Obi-Wan sent to the planet [Naboo](/wiki/Naboo "Naboo") to resolve a political
conflict involving the Trade Federation, a corrupt business conglomerate that
has blockaded the planet for political leverage. On arrival they are attacked
by their host. The Jedi retreat to the planet and rescue its besieged Queen,
[Padmé Amidala](/wiki/Padm%C3%A9_Amidala "Padmé Amidala"). Their attempt to
run the blockade and make way for the galactic capital of
[Coruscant](/wiki/Coruscant "Coruscant") succeeds, but the queen's ship is
damaged and is forced to land on the backwater planet of
[Tatooine](/wiki/Tatooine "Tatooine") for repairs.

While searching for replacement parts on Tatooine, Qui-Gon discovers a slave
boy, [Anakin Skywalker](/wiki/Anakin_Skywalker "Anakin Skywalker"), who is
extraordinarily strong in the Force; a test of his blood reveals that his
midi-chlorian count—a measure of Force potential—is the highest ever detected.
Qui-Gon is even more intrigued when Anakin's mother, Shmi, tells him that the
boy [had no father](/wiki/Miraculous_births "Miraculous births"). Realising
Anakin might be the "Chosen One" of Jedi lore destined to bring balance to the
Force, Qui-Gon bets Anakin's freedom and the spaceship parts on a pod race,
which Anakin wins. The entourage leave Tatooine, but not before Qui-Gon is
attacked by an unknown [Sith Lord](/wiki/Sith "Sith"), whom he fights off.
Upon returning to Coruscant, Jinn asks the Jedi Council to allow Anakin to be
trained as a Jedi. Master [Yoda](/wiki/Yoda "Yoda") senses fear in the boy,
and the Council refuses his request. Undaunted, Qui-Gon vows that he himself
will train Anakin when Obi-Wan becomes a Jedi Knight.

The two Jedi, [R2-D2](/wiki/R2-D2 "R2-D2") and Amidala return to Naboo to
liberate the planet. There, the trio are confronted by the Sith Lord from
earlier, who reveals himself as [Darth Maul](/wiki/Darth_Maul "Darth Maul").
After an arduous [lightsaber](/wiki/Lightsaber "Lightsaber") duel, Maul
mortally wounds Jinn, but is subsequently defeated by Obi Wan. Before dying,
Qui-Gon makes Obi-Wan promise he will train Anakin.[2]

Neeson was nominated for a 2000 [Saturn Award](/wiki/Saturn_Award "Saturn
Award") [Best Actor](/wiki/Saturn_Award_for_Best_Actor "Saturn Award for Best
Actor") award for his portrayal of Qui-Gon Jinn.[3]

#### _Attack of the Clones_ (2002)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-
Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=4 "Edit section: Attack of the Clones \(2002\)")]

In _[Attack of the Clones](/wiki/Attack_of_the_Clones "Attack of the Clones")_
, Yoda hears Qui-Gon's voice cry out to Anakin through the Force as Anakin
slaughters a tribe of [Tusken Raiders](/wiki/Tusken_Raider "Tusken Raider").
Obi-Wan discovers that Qui-Gon's old master, [Count Dooku](/wiki/Count_Dooku
"Count Dooku"), has become a Sith Lord; and Dooku mentions Qui-Gon as he
interrogates a captured Obi-Wan, expressing grief over his former apprentice's
death and arguing that Qui-Gon would have followed him in leaving the Republic
had he survived.

#### _Revenge of the Sith_ (2005)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-
Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=5 "Edit section: Revenge of the Sith \(2005\)")]

In _[Revenge of the
Sith](/wiki/Star_Wars:_Episode_III_%E2%80%93_Revenge_of_the_Sith "Star Wars:
Episode III – Revenge of the Sith")_ , Yoda reveals to Obi-Wan that Qui-Gon
has returned from the "netherworld of the Force" in order to teach both of
them how to retain one's consciousness after death. In a deleted scene, Yoda
mentally hears his voice before the arriving of senator [Bail
Organa](/wiki/Bail_Organa "Bail Organa"). In the
[novelization](/wiki/Novelization "Novelization"), Yoda finally admits that
Qui-Gon was indeed a great Jedi Master.

[Liam Neeson](/wiki/Liam_Neeson "Liam Neeson") was originally asked to record
some lines of Qui-Gon for the film's deleted scene included in the
novelization in which Yoda was going to speak with him. However, the scene was
cut from the film despite being present at the screenplay and Neeson's voice
was never recorded.[4]

### Television[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=6
"Edit section: Television")]

#### _The Clone Wars_ (2008–2014)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-
Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=7 "Edit section: The Clone Wars \(2008–2014\)")]

In _[Star Wars: The Clone
Wars](/wiki/Star_Wars:_The_Clone_Wars_\(2008_TV_series\) "Star Wars: The Clone
Wars \(2008 TV series\)")_ , the character is mentioned several times
throughout the series. Qui-Gon appears in two episodes of the third season. On
the mysterious planet [Mortis](/wiki/Mortis_\(Star_Wars\) "Mortis \(Star
Wars\)"), he informs Obi-Wan in the episode "Overlords" and later Anakin in
the episode "Ghosts of Mortis" about the three beings who believe, like Qui-
Gon, that Anakin is the Chosen One: the Father (the Unifying Force
manifestation), the Daughter (the light side incarnation) and the Son (the
dark side embodiment).[5] Later in the sixth-season episode "Voices," Yoda is
contacted by the disembodied voice of Qui-Gon. Despite his presence on Mortis,
Qui-Gon is revealed to have not been able to manifest a semi-physical form.
Following his deceased friend's instructions, Yoda goes on a quest across the
galaxy in order to learn the secrets of becoming one with the Force as well.
During one of the tests of the Force Priestesses, an illusion of Qui-Gon
appears along with Jedi Master Count Dooku and Obi-Wan.[6] It is only after
Yoda passes his test that he is allowed to learn Qui-Gon's technique to retain
one's consciousness after death.

#### _Star Wars Rebels_ (2014-2018)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-
Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=8 "Edit section: Star Wars Rebels
\(2014-2018\)")]

In _[Star Wars Rebels](/wiki/Star_Wars_Rebels "Star Wars Rebels")_ while he
does not appear nor he is mentioned, Obi-Wan finally avenges Qui-Gon Jinn's
death in the season 3 episode "[Twin Suns](/wiki/Twin_Suns "Twin Suns")",
where Kenobi and Darth Maul have their final duel on the planet Tatooine. Obi-
Wan uses Qui-Gon's favored form of lightsaber combat to bait Maul into
overextending himself, allowing him to easily slay him.

Qui-Gon's voice can be heard briefly in the season 4 episode "[A World Between
Worlds](/wiki/A_World_Between_Worlds "A World Between Worlds")" among a huge
number of voices from other major _Star Wars_ characters throughout all three
eras, demonstrating how the eponymous realm that [Ezra
Bridger](/wiki/Ezra_Bridger "Ezra Bridger") enters widely spans all time and
space in the _Star Wars_ universe.

### Novels[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=9 "Edit
section: Novels")]

In 2018, a year before the twentieth anniversary of _The Phantom Menace_ ,
[Lucasfilm](/wiki/Lucasfilm "Lucasfilm") and its current parent company, [The
Walt Disney Company](/wiki/The_Walt_Disney_Company "The Walt Disney Company"),
announced that a new novel involving Qui-Gon Jinn and Obi-Wan Kenobi, set
before the events of _Menace_ and titled _Master and Apprentice_ , will be
written by [Claudia Gray](/wiki/Claudia_Gray "Claudia Gray") and released on
February 26, 2019.[7]

### Legends[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=11
"Edit section: Legends")]

With the 2012 acquisition of [Lucasfilm](/wiki/Lucasfilm "Lucasfilm") by [The
Walt Disney Company](/wiki/The_Walt_Disney_Company "The Walt Disney Company"),
most of the licensed _Star Wars_ novels and comics produced since the
originating 1977 film _[Star Wars](/wiki/Star_Wars_\(film\) "Star Wars
\(film\)")_ were rebranded as _Star Wars Legends_ and declared non-canon to
the franchise in April 2014.[8][9][10]

#### Television[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=12
"Edit section: Television")]

##### _Clone Wars_ (2003-05)[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-
Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=13 "Edit section: Clone Wars \(2003-05\)")]

In _[Star Wars: Clone Wars](/wiki/Star_Wars:_Clone_Wars_\(2003_TV_series\)
"Star Wars: Clone Wars \(2003 TV series\)")_ , Qui-Gon makes a [cameo
appearance](/wiki/Cameo_appearance "Cameo appearance") in "Chapter 21". During
Yoda's Force dream, Qui-Gon tells Anakin to enter the mysterious cave on
[Dagobah](/wiki/Dagobah "Dagobah") where the boy will see a vision of his
future. Later when Obi-Wan reprimands Anakin for being late for his secret
Knighthood ceremony, Anakin replies "as far as your wisdom goes, you're no
Qui-Gon Jinn!". Though this saddens Obi-Wan, Anakin quickly apologizes, to
which Obi-Wan responds that he too misses Qui-Gon, often looking to his memory
for guidance and that Obi-Wan has done his best to pass his teaching onto
Anakin.[11]

#### Novels[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=14
"Edit section: Novels")]

Qui-Gon's life years prior to _The Phantom Menace_ is mainly detailed in the
_[Jedi Apprentice](/wiki/Star_Wars:_Jedi_Apprentice "Star Wars: Jedi
Apprentice")_ book series. In _[The Rising Force](/wiki/The_Rising_Force "The
Rising Force")_ (set 12 years before _The Phantom Menace_), Yoda encourages
Qui-Gon to take a new Padawan learner, following the failure of his previous
apprentice [Xanatos](/wiki/List_of_Star_Wars_characters#Xanatos "List of Star
Wars characters"), who turned to the dark side of the Force years before. Qui-
Gon observes a small lightsaber tournament among a group of the Temple's older
students, which includes 12-year-old Obi-Wan. He takes notice of Obi-Wan's
skills, but also of the boy's uncontrolled anger and refuses to train him.
Shortly following the tournament, the Jedi Knight leaves for a mission to the
planet [Bandomeer](/w/index.php?title=Bandomeer&action=edit&redlink=1
"Bandomeer \(page does not exist\)"). On the transport ship, Qui-Gon is
reunited with Obi-Wan, who is also being sent to Bandomeer to begin life as an
agricultural labourer. During the voyage, Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan help defend a
group of Arcona from the criminal organization Offworld Corporation. After
putting an end to the tense situation, the two arrive on Bandomeer, where Qui-
Gon receives a letter signed by his former apprentice Xanatos.[12]

In _[The Dark Rival](/wiki/The_Dark_Rival "The Dark Rival")_ , it is revealed
that the whole ordeal has been organized by Xanatos, now the leader of
Offworld. Qui-Gon sends Obi-Wan off to his Agri-Corps duties, while he plans
to meet with Xanatos to find an agreement between Offworld and Bandomeer.
However, Xanatos plans to [sabotage](/wiki/Sabotage "Sabotage") their meeting
and kill Qui-Gon. The Jedi Master duels with his former apprentice, and he and
Obi-Wan end Offworld's business on Bandomeer. Xanatos escapes, however. During
the encounter with Xanatos, Qui-Gon discovers Obi-Wan's true potential and
accepts the boy as his new Padawan. As a gift for Obi-Wan's 13th birthday,
Qui-Gon gives his apprentice a special rock he found from the River of Light
on his homeworld.[13] In _[The Captive Temple](/wiki/The_Captive_Temple "The
Captive Temple")_ , Xanatos attacks the Jedi Temple and nearly assassinates
Yoda, but Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan thwart his plans, and in _[The Day of
Reckoning](/wiki/The_Day_of_Reckoning_\(novel\) "The Day of Reckoning
\(novel\)")_ , when they chase Xanatos back to his homeworld
[Telos](/w/index.php?title=Telos_\(Star_Wars\)&action=edit&redlink=1 "Telos
\(Star Wars\) \(page does not exist\)"), the fallen Jedi refuses to surrender
and commits [suicide](/wiki/Suicide "Suicide"). Qui-Gon is thus able to bring
closure to a painful chapter of his life.[14][15]

In _[Legacy of the Jedi](/wiki/Legacy_of_the_Jedi "Legacy of the Jedi")_ , set
during both Qui-Gon's Padawan and Knight years, Qui-Gon and his master Dooku
are sent to accompany Senator Blix Annon on a [diplomatic](/wiki/Diplomacy
"Diplomacy") assignment. However, space [pirates](/wiki/Pirate "Pirate")
infiltrate their ship and their leader turns out to be rogue Jedi Lorian Nod,
a former friend of Dooku's. The two battle and Dooku lets his anger get the
best of him, but Qui-Gon prevents his master from violating the Jedi Code by
committing cold-blooded [murder](/wiki/Murder "Murder"). Years after their
first encounter, Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan encounter Nod and once again the fallen
Jedi is incarcerated for his crimes.[16]

In _[Secrets of the Jedi](/wiki/Secrets_of_the_Jedi "Secrets of the Jedi")_
(set seven years before _The Phantom Menace_), Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan are paired
with Jedi Master [Adi Gallia](/wiki/List_of_Star_Wars_characters#Adi_Gallia
"List of Star Wars characters") and her Padawan [Siri
Tachi](/wiki/List_of_Star_Wars_characters#Siri_Tachi "List of Star Wars
characters"). The mission, which results in Qui-Gon and Adi being separated
from Obi-Wan and Siri, leads to the discovery of romantic feelings between the
two Jedi Padawans. Qui-Gon detects these emotions and warns Obi-Wan of his own
example with [Tahl](/wiki/List_of_Star_Wars_characters#Tahl "List of Star Wars
characters"), a female Jedi whose murder nearly pushed Qui-Gon over the edge
to the dark side.[17]

In _[Cloak of Deception](/wiki/Cloak_of_Deception "Cloak of Deception")_ (set
a year before _The Phantom Menace_), both Jedi fight against a
[terrorist](/wiki/Terrorist "Terrorist") organization called the Nebula Front,
who are secretly following [Darth Sidious](/wiki/Palpatine "Palpatine")'
orders. At the Trade Federation conference on
[Eriadu](/w/index.php?title=Eriadu&action=edit&redlink=1 "Eriadu \(page does
not exist\)"), Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan successfully defend Chancellor Valorum, but
do not prevent the deaths of the rest of the Trade Federation Directorate,
allowing the Neimoidians to take control of the Federation.[18]

#### In comic books[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-
Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=15 "Edit section: In comic books")]

Aside from the graphic novelization of _The Phantom Menace_ , Qui-Gon appears
infrequently in _Star Wars_ -related comic books. His most extensive
appearance thus far is in the "Stark Hyperspace War" plotline in _[Star Wars:
Republic](/wiki/Star_Wars:_Republic "Star Wars: Republic")_. In this [story
arc](/wiki/Story_arc "Story arc"), which takes place during the same year Qui-
Gon takes Obi-Wan as his apprentice, Qui-Gon and Obi-Wan fight in the titular
conflict along with other Jedi such as [Plo
Koon](/wiki/List_of_Star_Wars_characters#Plo_Koon "List of Star Wars
characters") and [Quinlan Vos](/wiki/List_of_Star_Wars_characters#Quinlan_Vos
"List of Star Wars characters"), and Qui-Gon ends up saving Nute Gunray, the
future Trade Federation viceroy.[19]

## Reception[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Qui-Gon_Jinn&action=edit&section=16
"Edit section: Reception")]

Despite the mixed reviews that the prequel trilogy received from various movie
critics, Liam Neeson's performance and character received positive reviews.
Colin Kennedy from [Empire Online](/wiki/Empire_Online "Empire Online") stated
in his review of the film, " Liam Neeson has manfully carried the action on
his shoulders throughout (the subsequent prequels desperately miss him) and
his final words – “Obi-Wan, promise... Promise me you will train the boy” -
provide the movie with its only real weight.[20] Owen Gleiberman from
[Entertainment Weekly](/wiki/Entertainment_Weekly "Entertainment Weekly") said
in his review of _The Phantom Menace_ , "If there’s an actor who holds _The
Phantom Menace_ together, it’s Liam Neeson. Tersely commanding, he gives the
film its only hints of emotional dynamism." [21]

In 2017, _[Rolling Stone](/wiki/Rolling_Stone "Rolling Stone")_ placed Qui-Gon
Jinn at the number 25 spot on their 50 Best _Star Wars_ Characters of All Time
list.[22]

As revealed in _The Art of Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace_ , director
[George Lucas](/wiki/George_Lucas "George Lucas") conceived the character of
Qui-Gon Jinn during pre-production of the film. This is shown by concept art
where Obi-Wan Kenobi is shown alone in the Trade Federation flagship and while
meeting Jar Jar Binks. Even when Qui-Gon was conceived, Lucas toyed with
making him the younger Jedi, as shown in concept art depicting Obi-Wan as an
old man. Lucas originally envisioned an [American](/wiki/United_States "United
States") actor for the role of Qui-Gon, but ultimately cast [Northern
Irish](/wiki/Northern_Irish_people "Northern Irish people") actor [Liam
Neeson](/wiki/Liam_Neeson "Liam Neeson") because he considered Neeson to have
great skills and presence, describing him as a "master actor, who the other
actors will look up to, who has got the qualities of strength that the
character demands."[23] Initially, Lucas had planned for Qui-Gon to have long
white hair, but that idea was scrapped and Qui-Gon is depicted as having long
brown hair in the film.

During the early development of _[Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the
Sith](/wiki/Star_Wars:_Episode_III_-_Revenge_of_the_Sith "Star Wars: Episode
III - Revenge of the Sith")_ , Lucas wrote a scene featuring a ghostly Qui-Gon
speaking with [Yoda](/wiki/Yoda "Yoda") about Anakin. [Liam
Neeson](/wiki/Liam_Neeson "Liam Neeson") was set to reprise his role, because
he hinted his possible appearance in the film.[24] However, the scene was
finally deleted from the film and Neeson was never recorded, although the
scene was retained in the film's novelization.[25]

The character's name is derived from the Chinese word _[qigong](/wiki/Qigong
"Qigong")_ (气功 or 氣功), a system of coordinated body movement, breathing, and
meditation used for health, spirituality, and martial arts training that
allows access to higher realms of awareness, and balance of life energy,
similar to [Tai chi](/wiki/Tai_chi "Tai chi"). This is paired with the Arabic
word _[Jinn](/wiki/Jinn "Jinn")_ , meaning "genie" or "tutelary spirit." The
name translates almost literally as "Guardian Spirit of the Living Force."[26]
"Jinn" could also refer to the Chinese word for power, _jin_ (勁), and the
martial arts concept of _[fa jin](/wiki/Fa_jin "Fa jin")_ , which is the
explosive release of internal strength or power.[27]
